James de Villiers, News24Hout Bay. (Duncan Alfreds, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - The Western Cape African National Congress plans to lodge a complaint with the SA Human Rights Commission and police on Monday after a Hout Bay resident apparently called black people &ldquo;stupid animals&rdquo; in a Facebook post.&ldquo;They are like stupid animals. We should tie them to a rope. Too many Africans flocking to Hout Bay. Draw up a petition. Soon there will be nothing left of Hout Bay,&rdquo; read the post Vanessa Hartley made on the Hout Bay Complete Facebook page.It was posted on Sunday and had since been removed.READ: Penny Sparrow suffers another setback in courtANC Western Cape spokesperson Yonele Diko said a complaint would be lodged with the SA Human Rights Commission at 14:00 on Monday and a case opened with police.&ldquo;We believe the majority of people in South Africa do not share these views. Racist will never have the final word in this country.&rdquo;Democratic Alliance ward councillor for Hout Bay, Roberto Miguel Quintas, said he condemned Hartley&rsquo;s comments.&ldquo;I personally am working extremely hard on this for the people of Hout Bay and am grossly disappointed when I see threads of this nature,&rdquo; Quintas replied to Hartley&rsquo;s comment.&ldquo;We shouldn&rsquo;t allow society to be divided by this type of racist agenda,&rdquo; DA Western Cape spokesperson Anneke Scheepers said.Hartley could not be reached for comment.Here's a screen grab of the post before it was removed: 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.